<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="498" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[149,786,690,742]" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">Variations.—The rostrum is more excavated in the larger paratypes, and the larger chela is more globose.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[149,787,768,908]" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">
Morphometry.—Holotype male with LC 16.89 mm. Paratypes (
<emphasis box="[227,240,797,820]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">n</emphasis>
= 5) with mean LC 13.60 mm. Asmall-sized species. LPC/LF ratios of paratypes (
<emphasis box="[559,572,826,849]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">n</emphasis>
= 3) ranging from 1.50 to 1.90.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[149,787,768,908]" box="[175,787,885,908]" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">CA/LA ratios of paratypes varying little, from 1.7 to 1.8.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="498" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[149,786,932,986]" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">Distribution.—Brazil: State of Santa Catarina, Rio Itajaí- Açú Basin.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="498" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[149,787,1011,1824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">
Remarks.—The Bayesian phylogenetic analysis of the molecular data showed that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bond-Buckup &amp; Jara &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Bueno &amp; Crandall &amp; Santos" authorityYear="2010" box="[456,595,1041,1064]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pomerana">
<emphasis box="[456,595,1041,1064]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">A. pomerana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to Clade Cas defined in 
<bibRefCitation author="Perez-Losada, M. &amp; G. Bond-Buckup &amp; C. G. Jara &amp; K. A. Crandall" box="[324,615,1069,1092]" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Biology" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" pagination="767 - 780" part="53" refId="ref5388" refString="Perez-Losada, M., G. Bond-Buckup, C. G. Jara, and K. A. Crandall. 2004. Molecular systematics and biogeography of the southern South American fresh-water '' crabs '' Aegla (Decapoda: Anomura: Aeglidae) using multiple heuristic tree search approaches. Systematic Biology 53: 767 - 780." title="Molecular systematics and biogeography of the southern South American fresh-water '' crabs '' Aegla (Decapoda: Anomura: Aeglidae) using multiple heuristic tree search approaches" type="journal article" year="2004">Pérez-Losada et al. (2004)</bibRefCitation>
. With regard to the relationship to other species, this was considered a sister-species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Buckup and Rossi, 1977" authorityName="Buckup &amp; Rossi" authorityYear="1977" box="[334,500,1128,1151]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leptodactyla">
<emphasis box="[334,500,1128,1151]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">A. leptodactyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[519,584,1128,1151]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[159,190,1696,1715]" captionTargetBox="[326,1316,173,1671]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[326,1316,173,1671]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. Maximum likelihood and Bayesian trees as modified from Pérez-Losada et al. (2009). Posterior probabilities (if&gt; 0.5) are indicated for each clade. Aegla pomerana and Aegla muelleri are presented in bold" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3568304" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3568304/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), which occurs in the Rio Uruguay basin on the high plateau of Rio Grande do Sul and Santa Catarina. Nevertheless, there are several morphological differences between these two species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bond-Buckup &amp; Jara &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Bueno &amp; Crandall &amp; Santos" authorityYear="2010" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pomerana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">A. pomerana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not bear an extra-orbital sinus, whereas 
<taxonomicName authority="Buckup and Rossi, 1977" authorityName="Buckup &amp; Rossi" authorityYear="1977" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leptodactyla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">A. leptodactyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
possesses this character. The rostrum of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bond-Buckup &amp; Jara &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Bueno &amp; Crandall &amp; Santos" authorityYear="2010" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pomerana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">A. pomerana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only slightly ligulate, recurved, lacks a carina on the distal third, and ends without a spine on the tip; whereas this structure in 
<taxonomicName authority="Buckup and Rossi, 1977" authorityName="Buckup &amp; Rossi" authorityYear="1977" box="[446,616,1362,1385]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leptodactyla">
<emphasis box="[446,616,1362,1385]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">A. leptodactyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is of medium length, and its distal end terminates in a spine. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bond-Buckup &amp; Jara &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Bueno &amp; Crandall &amp; Santos" authorityYear="2010" box="[649,787,1391,1414]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pomerana">
<emphasis box="[649,787,1391,1414]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">A. pomerana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has wide chelipeds; its sister species has narrow chelipeds.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[149,787,1011,1824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">
The relationship of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bond-Buckup &amp; Jara &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Bueno &amp; Crandall &amp; Santos" authorityYear="2010" box="[396,538,1450,1473]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pomerana">
<emphasis box="[396,538,1450,1473]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">A. pomerana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with species found in the Rio Uruguay basin, which at present has no direct connection to the Rio Itajaí basin, can be attributed to a common geological origin of the two basins, which is related to the formation of the Serra Geral in southern Brazil (
<bibRefCitation author="Ribeiro, A. C." box="[156,309,1596,1619]" journalOrPublisher="Neotropical Ichthyology" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" pagination="225 - 246" part="4" refId="ref5492" refString="Ribeiro, A. C. 2006. Tectonic history and the biogeography of the freshwater fishes from the coastal drainages of eastern Brazil: an example of faunal evolution associated with a divergent continental margin. Neotropical Ichthyology 4: 225 - 246." title="Tectonic history and the biogeography of the freshwater fishes from the coastal drainages of eastern Brazil: an example of faunal evolution associated with a divergent continental margin" type="journal article" year="2006">Ribeiro, 2006</bibRefCitation>
). The uplift of the Serra Geral separated the Uruguay and Itajaí-Açú rivers creating the opportunity for new species to arise through allopatric speciation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[149,787,1011,1824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">
Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bond-Buckup &amp; Jara &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Bueno &amp; Crandall &amp; Santos" authorityYear="2010" box="[372,514,1685,1708]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pomerana">
<emphasis box="[372,514,1685,1708]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">A. pomerana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Bond-Buckup and Buckup, 1994" authorityName="Bond-Buckup and Buckup" authorityYear="1994" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis box="[642,787,1685,1708]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">A. marginata</emphasis>
Bond-Buckup and Buckup, 1994
</taxonomicName>
, in some aspects, particularly in the slightly arched antero-lateral border of the carapace. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bond-Buckup &amp; Jara &amp; Buckup &amp; Pérez-Losada &amp; Bueno &amp; Crandall &amp; Santos" authorityYear="2010" box="[414,554,1772,1795]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pomerana">
<emphasis box="[414,554,1772,1795]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">A. pomerana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a subrectangular palmar crest, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bond-Buckup and Buckup" authorityYear="1994" box="[345,488,1801,1824]" class="Malacostraca" family="Aeglidae" genus="Aegla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis box="[345,488,1801,1824]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="498">A. marginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has no palmar crest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
